#MEM id=references source=/root/yvon/agent-department/COO/diana/skills/marketplace/traction-eos/references/data.md savings=1%
M|Data|tx|The Data cp replaces gut-feeling management w/ objective, weekly numbers. When everyone in the leadership team looks at the same 5-15 metrics every week, problems surface weeks earlier, accountability becomes automatic, and decision-making improves dramatically. This guide covers how to ds a Scorecard, choose the right metrics, avoid common mistakes, and connect data to your Level 10 meetings.
M|The |tx|A Scorecard is a one-page document that tracks 5-15 activity-based numbers weekly. It is reviewed in every Level 10 meeting. If a number is off track, it drops to the Issues List for IDS.
M|Scor|tx|1. **Weekly cadence.** Monthly financials are too slow. By the time you see a monthly miss, you have lost four weeks of correction time. Weekly numbers give you early wn.
M|Scor|tx|2. **Activity-based metrics.** Measure what people do (calls made, demos given), not just what happened (rv, churn). Activities are leading indicators you can influence. Results are lagging indicators you can only observe.
M|Scor|tx|3. **5-15 numbers.** Fewer than 5 means blind spots. More than 15 means noise. Most companies land on 8-12.
M|Scor|tx|4. **Every number has an owner.** One person is accountable for each metric. Not a department. A name.
M|Scor|tx|5. **Every number has a goal.** A number w/o a goal is just a data point. The goal creates the standard for red/green tracking.
M|The |Ask |"If I went on vacation for four weeks w/ no phone or em, what 5-15 numbers wld I want to see when I got back to know exactly how the business performed?"
M|The |tx|This question forces you to identify the vital few numbers that genuinely indicate business health.
M|Metr|tx|\| Category \| What to Measure \| Example Metrics \|
M|Metr|tx|\|----------\|----------------\|-----------------\|
M|Metr|tx|\| **rv** \| Money coming in \| Weekly rv, new deal value, average deal size \|
M|Metr|tx|\| **Pipeline** \| Future rv \| New leads generated, qualified opportunities, proposals sent \|
M|Metr|tx|\| **Sales Activity** \| Effort going in \| Calls made, demos done, meetings booked \|
M|Metr|tx|\| **cs Health** \| Retention and satisfaction \| Churn rate, NPS, support tickets resolved, renewal rate \|
M|Metr|tx|\| **Operations** \| Delivery qual \| On-time delivery %, defect rate, utilization rate \|
M|Metr|tx|\| **Financial** \| Cash and profitability \| Cash balance, AR over 60 days, gross margin \|
M|Metr|tx|\| **People** \| Team health \| Open positions, employee satisfaction score, training hours \|
M|Lead|tx|Understanding the difference btw leading and lagging indicators is ct to building an effective Scorecard.
M|Lead|tx|\| tp \| Definition \| rp Time \| Examples \|
M|Lead|tx|\|------\|-----------\|--------------\|---------\|
M|Lead|tx|\| **Leading** \| Measures input activities that drive future results \| Can be corrected this week \| Calls made, proposals sent, cn published \|
M|Lead|tx|\| **Lagging** \| Measures output results that have already occurred \| Can only be observed, not changed retroactively \| rv, churn, profit margin \|
M|Lead|tx|**The ideal Scorecard is 70% leading indicators and 30% lagging indicators.** Leading indicators let you course-correct before lagging indicators go red.
M|Buil|Grea|
M|Buil|tx|```
M|Buil|tx|Outbound emails (leading)
M|Buil|tx|→ Meetings booked (leading)
M|Buil|tx|→ Demos given (leading)
M|Buil|tx|→ Proposals sent (leading)
M|Buil|tx|→ Deals closed (lagging)
M|Buil|tx|→ rv (lagging)
M|Buil|tx|```
M|Buil|tx|When rv drops, you can trace back through the chain to find where the breakdown occurred. Was it fewer emails? Lower meeting conversion? Longer sales cycles? The Scorecard tells you.
M|The |Each|
M|The |it|Reports the number weekly in the Level 10 meeting
M|The |it|Explains when the number is off track
M|The |it|Owns the plan to get it back on track
M|The |it|Drops it to the Issues List when help is needed
M|The |tx|**Ownership does not mean they do all the work.** The VP of Sales owns the "demos done" metric even though individual reps give the demos. Ownership means accountability for the result.
M|Assi|tx|\| Metric \| Owner \| Why \|
M|Assi|tx|\|--------\|-------\|-----\|
